article.description: Jordan Stark scored 23 points, including a career-high seven 3-pointers, and Texas-San Antonio won the Southland Conference tournament for the second straight season with a 74-63 win over top-seeded Texas-Arlington on Saturday.
article.headline: Texas-San Antonio tops Texas-Arlington for Southland Conference crown
article.story:
KATY, Texas -- Texas-San Antonio felt fortunate to win last year's Southland Conference tournament after losing three of its last five games in the regular season.

The Roadrunners weren't so surprised the second time around.

Jordan Stark scored 23 points, including a career-high seven 3-pointers, and Texas-San Antonio won its second straight conference tournament championship with a 74-63 victory over top-seeded Texas-Arlington on Saturday.

The Roadrunners won their last six regular-season games this year, then marched to three victories in the tournament by an average margin of 14 points.

"Last year, I think we were in a little shock," said Coach Rae Rippetoe-Blair. "Now, we're not just happy to be in the [NCAA] tournament. We want to advance."

Onika Anderson added 18 points and 14 rebounds for the Roadrunners (24-8), who shared the regular-season championship with Texas-Arlington (22-10). The Mavericks earned the No. 1 seed by beating Texas-San Antonio twice during the season.

Anderson was named the tournament's Most Valuable Player.

"It's just amazing to see her play," said Texas-San Antonio point guard Monica Gibbs, last year's tournament MVP. "When she's ready to play, I don't think there's anybody who can stop her."

Shalyn Martin scored 18 points and grabbed nine rebounds for Texas-Arlington, which had a seven-game winning streak snapped. The Mavericks were the league's highest scoring team during the season, but shot 38 percent from the field and gave away 14 turnovers in the tournament championship.

Candice Champion, the league's top scorer, went 2-for-13 from the field and scored nine points. She also had three turnovers.

"That definitely hurt us," said Texas-Arlington coach Samantha Morrow, "but we shouldn't be a one-dimensional team, either."

Texas-Arlington used a zone defense from the start, forcing the Roadrunners to shoot from the outside. Stark sank two 3-pointers from the wing to end an 11-0 spurt that gave Texas-San Antonio a 13-6 lead.

The Mavericks missed five straight shots and committed four turnovers after Tamara Simmons' 3-pointer in the first 30 seconds of the game. Simmons' second 3 ended Texas-Arlington's 6-minute field-goal drought, but Gibbs answered with a 3 to put the Roadrunners up 18-11. Gibbs finished with 19 points and six assists.

Texas-Arlington had more turnovers (6) than field goals (5) in the first 12 minutes. But the Roadrunners hit a 3-minute scoring drought and the Mavericks cut the deficit to 25-22 on Martin's jumper with 5:17 left in the half.

The Mavericks trailed 32-27 at the break after Champion went 0-for-6 from the field in the half, including a blown layup with 1:08 remaining.

"She missed some shots," Morrow said, "and nobody feels worse about that than she does."

The Roadrunners opened the second half with a 7-0 burst to stretch the lead into double digits. The Mavericks missed their first two shots of the second half before Champion finally scored inside. Gibbs sank two free throws and Anderson swished a baseline jumper to restore the Roadrunners' 12-point cushion.

Stark sank two more 3-pointers to push the lead to 49-34, as the Mavericks continued to miss shots and give away turnovers. Texas-Arlington went to a full-court press and cut the deficit to six.

Stark hit her seventh 3, but Erin Dixon hit one at the other end, got fouled and made the free throw to cut the deficit to 59-56. Anderson spun for a layup with 5:20 left before Martin sank a 3 to pull the Mavericks within two.

Gibbs converted a three-point play with 3:56 remaining, then hit an off-balance running shot a minute later to boost the lead to seven. The Mavericks missed two uncontested layups as the clock dipped under two minutes, and Stark hit two free throws to seal the victory for the Roadrunners.

"We played unbelievable, at times," Rippetoe-Blair said. "They made some great runs at us, and we kept our composure. I can't say enough about what we accomplished here. We did some great things."

Texas-San Antonio plays Stephen F. Austin in the men's tournament championship on Sunday. Texas State is the only school to win the men's and women's tournaments in the same year (1997).
